         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="vol-2-B_M-d2e39292-person" n="vol-2-B_M-Meshulam-1">
               <sex cert="high">M</sex>
               <persName type="lemma">משלם</persName>
               <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Meshulam</persName><ref type="note" corresp="#d1006e4"/>
               <state type="desc">
                  <note>Epiphanius (2)’s son, aged 25<ref type="note" corresp="#d2e39307"/>
                  </note>
               </state>
               <state type="provenance">
                  <note>Epitaph, Zoar</note>
               </state>
               <bibl>IPT1a, no. 251</bibl>
               <state type="addl-Descr">
                  <note>Jew?<ref type="note" corresp="#d2e39326"/>
                  </note>
               </state>
               <floruit>498<ref type="note" corresp="#d2e39335"/>
               </floruit>
               <note xml:id="d2e39297" n="1"> There are many forms
                                for this name in LXX, see H &amp; R Suppl. 114. The nearest to this
                                one is <span xml:lang="gr"></span>. This is
                                probably another variation on it.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e39307" n="2">
                                In Greek –<span xml:lang="gr"></span>. On these
                                see details vol. 3, Introduction 3.1, p. 21.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e39326" n="3"> The inscription
                                mentions <span xml:lang="gr"></span> (one God who rules all)
                                but this is no indication of Jewishness, especially not in Zoar, see
                                Introduction 6.1.6. The inscription is neither specifically
                                Christian, nor undoubtedly pagan. Since the Zoar cemetery includes
                                Jewish tombstones, this one could also be Jewish, see Introduction
                                6.2.1.1.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e39335" n="4">
                                The inscription is dated according to the era of the Province of
                                Arabia, see Introduction 7.5.2.2.</note>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
